@page "/aquaponics"

<!-- ========================= -->
<!-- HERO (dark green) -->
<!-- ========================= -->
<section class="hero">
    <div class="section-inner">
        <h1>What Is Aquaponics?</h1>
        <p>
            Aquaponics is a sustainable farming method that grows fish and plants together in a 
            closed‑loop system. Fish produce nutrient‑rich waste, beneficial bacteria convert that 
            waste into plant fertilizer, and the plants clean the water for the fish.
        </p>
        <p>
            For this honors project, aquaponics serves as the foundation for a conceptual model of 
            how sustainable food systems could operate in urban environments like Chicagoland.
        </p>
    </div>
</section>

<div class="divider-coral"></div>

<!-- ========================= -->
<!-- WHY AQUAPONICS MATTERS (pale coral) -->
<!-- ========================= -->
<section class="pale-coral">
    <div class="section-inner">
        <h2>Why Aquaponics Matters</h2>
        <p>
            Aquaponics uses up to <strong>90% less water</strong> than traditional farming, requires 
            no soil, and can produce fresh food year‑round — even during harsh Chicago winters. 
            In this project, aquaponics is explored as a proof‑of‑concept approach for climate‑resilient, 
            resource‑efficient food production.
        </p>
    </div>
</section>

<div class="divider-blue"></div>

<!-- ========================= -->
<!-- OUR FISH (pale blue) -->
<!-- ========================= -->
<section class="pale-blue">
    <div class="section-inner">
        <h2>Our Fish: Nile Tilapia (Conceptual)</h2>
        <p>
            This project models the use of <strong>Nile tilapia</strong>, a hardy freshwater species 
            commonly used in real aquaponic systems. Tilapia grow quickly, tolerate a wide range of 
            conditions, and are frequently studied as a reliable protein source in sustainable agriculture.
            In this honors project, tilapia are used as a theoretical example rather than an active stock.
        </p>
    </div>
</section>

<div class="divider-coral"></div>

<!-- ========================= -->
<!-- OUR PLANTS (dark green) -->
<!-- ========================= -->
<section class="why-aquaponics">
    <div class="section-inner">
        <h2>Our Plants: Buttercrisp Lettuce (Conceptual)</h2>
        <p>
            The system design features <strong>buttercrisp lettuce</strong>, a leafy green known for 
            thriving in aquaponic environments. While no crops are being grown as part of this academic 
            project, buttercrisp lettuce serves as a realistic model for how indoor aquaponics can 
            produce fast‑growing, nutritious greens.
        </p>
    </div>
</section>

<div class="divider-blue"></div>

<!-- ========================= -->
<!-- HOW THE SYSTEM WORKS (pale coral, card layout) -->
<!-- ========================= -->
<section class="pale-coral">
    <div class="section-inner">
        <h2>How the System Works (Modeled Process)</h2>

        <div class="steps">
            <div class="step">
                <h3><i class="fa-solid fa-fish"></i> Fish produce waste</h3>
                <p>Tilapia release ammonia into the water.</p>
            </div>

            <div class="step">
                <h3><i class="fa-solid fa-vial"></i> Bacteria convert the waste</h3>
                <p>Beneficial bacteria convert ammonia → nitrite → nitrate.</p>
            </div>

            <div class="step">
                <h3><i class="fa-solid fa-leaf"></i> Plants absorb nutrients</h3>
                <p>Lettuce grows in nutrient‑rich water.</p>
            </div>

            <div class="step">
                <h3><i class="fa-solid fa-arrows-rotate"></i> Clean water returns</h3>
                <p>Plants filter and return clean water to the fish.</p>
            </div>
        </div>

        <p>
            This cycle is presented as a conceptual model for educational purposes and is not an 
            active, physical system.
        </p>
    </div>
</section>

<div class="divider-coral"></div>

<!-- ========================= -->
<!-- WHY CHICAGO (pale blue, icon list) -->
<!-- ========================= -->
<section class="pale-blue">
    <div class="section-inner">
        <h2>Why We Chose Aquaponics for Chicago (Case Study)</h2>

        <ul class="icon-list">
            <li><i class="fa-solid fa-calendar"></i> Operates year‑round in controlled environments</li>
            <li><i class="fa-solid fa-snowflake"></i> Thrives indoors despite harsh winters</li>
            <li><i class="fa-solid fa-droplet"></i> Uses minimal water and no soil</li>
            <li><i class="fa-solid fa-seedling"></i> Produces predictable, consistent harvests</li>
            <li><i class="fa-solid fa-people-group"></i> Can support neighborhoods facing food insecurity</li>
            <li><i class="fa-solid fa-truck"></i> Reduces reliance on long‑distance supply chains</li>
        </ul>

        <p>
            In this project, Chicago serves as a case study for exploring how aquaponics could 
            theoretically support urban food systems.
        </p>
    </div>
</section>
